.TE
.SH DESCRIPTION
An object is async disposable if it has the
\f[CR][Symbol.asyncDispose]()\f[R] method.
The method is expected to have the following semantics:
.IP \(bu 2
Invoking this method notifies the AsyncDisposable object that the caller
does not intend to continue to use this object.
This method should perform any necessary logic to explicit clean up the
resource including, but not limited to, file system handles, streams,
host objects, etc.
.IP \(bu 2
This method can return a promise, which will be awaited before
continuing.
.IP \(bu 2
When an exception is thrown from this method, it typically means that
the resource could not be explicitly freed.
An AsyncDisposable object is not considered \(lqdisposed\(rq until the
resulting Promise has been fulfilled.
.IP \(bu 2
If called more than once on the same object, the function should not
throw an exception.
However, this requirement is not enforced.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS User defined async disposables
\f[CR][Symbol.asyncDispose]\f[R] allows the creation of custom async
disposables.
See the \f[CR]await using\f[R] reference for more information.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]class\f[R] Disposable {
  #fileHandle;
  #disposed;

  constructor(handle) {
    \f[B]this\f[R].#disposed = \f[B]false\f[R];
    \f[B]this\f[R].#fileHandle = handle;
  }

  \f[B]async\f[R] [Symbol.asyncDispose]() {
    \f[B]await\f[R] \f[B]this\f[R].#fileHandle.close();
    \f[B]this\f[R].disposed = \f[B]true\f[R];
  }

  \f[B]get\f[R] isDisposed() {
    \f[B]return\f[R] \f[B]this\f[R].disposed;
  }
}

\f[B]const\f[R] resource = \f[B]new\f[R] Disposable(\f[B]await\f[R] fs.open(\(dqmy\-file.txt\(dq, \(dqr\(dq));
{
  \f[B]await\f[R] using resourceUsed = resource;
  console.log(resource.isDisposed); \f[I]// false\f[R]
}
console.log(resource.isDisposed); \f[I]// true\f[R]
.EE
